@Linux Network Routing & NAT Architecture
#Network Topology
WAN Interface (enp0s3) -> External / Internet Access
LAN Interface (enp0s8) -> Gateway IP: 192.168.10.1/24
Client Node -> IP: 192.168.10.100 (Gateway/DNS pointed to Router)
#Kernel Level Routing (Layer 3)
Configuration: /etc/sysctl.conf
Key Parameter: net.ipv4.ip_forward=1
Function: Enables the kernel to act as a router by forwarding packets between interfaces
Verification: sysctl -p to commit changes without reboot

@Firewall & NAT Implementation (iptables)
#NAT & Masquerading
Table: nat | Chain: POSTROUTING
Rule: iptables -t nat -A POSTROUTING -o enp0s3 -j MASQUERADE
Purpose: Translates private LAN addresses to a single public WAN IP (IP Masquerading)
#Forwarding Logic (Stateful Inspection)
Outbound: LAN -> WAN (enp0s8 to enp0s3) -> ACCEPT
Inbound: WAN -> LAN (enp0s3 to enp0s8) -> ESTABLISHED, RELATED only
Security: Ensures only responses to internal requests can enter the LAN
#Persistence Strategy
Tool: iptables-persistent
Storage: /etc/iptables/rules.v4
Backup: Manual dump stored in /root/backup/iptable

@Network Services & Hardening
#DNS Resolution (BIND9)
Domain: my.network
Role: Local DNS Resolver for LAN clients
#Current Security Posture
Status: Firewall (UFW) currently DISABLED
Policy: Default INPUT chain set to ACCEPT (Caution: exposed interfaces)
Next Step: Implement UFW while migrating NAT rules to /etc/ufw/before.rules

@Operational Diagnostics
#Verification Commands
Routing Table -> route -n or ip route
Active NAT Rules -> iptables -t nat -L -v -n
Interface Statistics -> ip -s link show enp0s8
Connection Tracking -> conntrack -L (if installed, shows active NAT translations)
